<subsection><title>Percents</title>
<p>A <term>percent</term> is a fraction. For example,

    <me>75\% = 0.75 = \dfrac{75}{100}</me>

"Percent" means "for each 100" or "out of 100." So a percent is just a fraction whose denominator is 100. If you understand hundredths, you also understand percents!</p>
    <image source="coffee.png" width = "80%"></image>

<example><statement><p> Jaycee is an interior designer and takes a 10% commission on the cost of a remodel. A recent remodel cost $12,500. How much is Jaycee's commission?</p></statement>

<solution><p>10% means "ten out of 100" or <m>\dfrac{10}{100}</m>, and <m>\dfrac{10}{100}</m> reduces to <m>\dfrac{1}{10}</m>. To find <m>\dfrac{1}{10}</m> of 12,500, we divide by 10:
  <me>\dfrac{1}{10}~ \text{of}~ 12,500 = 12,500 \div 10 = 1250</me>
Jaycee's commission is $1250.</p></solution></example>

<p>Because 10% is equal to <m>\dfrac{1}{10},~</m> it is easy to find 10% of a number: we just divide the number by 10. Once we know 10% of a number, we can find other percents. For example, to find 20% of a number we can compute 10% of the number and then double the result.</p>

<exercise><statement><p>Viktor used a coupon for 10% off the price of hiking boots and saved 
$12.00. Find the following percents of the price of the boots.</p>
<p><ol marker = "a." cols="2">
  <li><p>5%</p></li>
  <li><p>20%</p></li>
  <li><p>25%</p></li>
  <li><p>1%</p></li>
  <li><p>3%</p></li>
  <li><p>100%</p></li>
</ol></p></statement>

<answer><p><ol marker = "a." cols="2">
  <li><p>$6</p></li>
  <li><p>$24</p></li>
  <li><p>$30</p></li>
  <li><p>$1.20</p></li>
  <li><p>$3.60</p></li>
  <li><p>$120</p></li>
</ol></p></answer></exercise>

