<subsection><title>What Percent Is It?</title>
<p>If you follow a diet of 2000 calories per day, your minimum daily requirement (MDR) of potassium is 3500 milligrams.</p>

<example><statement><p>A bowl of Cheerios provides 140 milligrams of potassium. What percent of your MDR is that?</p>
    <image source="cheerios.png" width = "45%"></image></statement>

<solution><p>We'd like to know what percent is 140 out of 3500. Remember that a percent is a fraction, so we make a fraction with the part (140) out of the whole (3500).

  <me>\dfrac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \dfrac{140}{3500} = 0.04 ~~~~~~~~\blert{\text{Divide 140 by 3500.}}</me>

As a decimal fraction, Cheerios provides 0.04, or 4 hundredths of the MDR for potassium. Four hundredths is the same as 4%. (Or you can multiply 0.04 by 100 to write it as a percent:  <m>0.04 \times 100 = 4%</m>)</p></solution></example>

<assemblage><title>To find what percent a part is</title>
<p><ol>
  <li><p>Divide the part by the whole.</p></li>
  <li><p>Multiply the decimal fraction by 100.</p></li>
</ol></p></assemblage>

