<subsection><title>Eighths</title>
<p>We have studied the benchmark fractions <m>\dfrac{1}{4},~~\dfrac{1}{2},~~</m> and <m>~\dfrac{3}{4},~~</m> as well as tenths and hundredths. Along the way we also encountered fifths. Here is another familiar and useful fraction.</p>

<example><statement><p>Nelson bought a quarter-pound of sliced roast beef and ate half of it for lunch. How many ounces of roast beef did he eat? What fraction of a pound is that?</p> 
    <image source="sandwich.png" width = "35%"></image></statement>

<solution><p>There are 16 ounces in a pound, so a quarter-pound is
  <me>\dfrac{1}{4}~ \text{of}~ 16 = 16 \div 4 = 4 ~~\text{ounces}</me>
  Half of 4 ounces is 2 ounces, so Nelson ate 2 ounces of roast beef. As a fraction of a pound, 2 ounces is
    <me>\dfrac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \dfrac{2}{16} = \dfrac{1}{8}~~~~~~\blert{\text{Reduce: divide top and bottom by 2.}} </me>           
Two ounces is <m>\dfrac{1}{8}</m> lb, or one-eighth of a pound.</p></solution></example>

<note><p>Recall that <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m> is one-half of <m>\dfrac{1}{2}</m>.  Now we see that <m>\dfrac{1}{8}</m> is one-half of <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m>. You know that the decimal form of <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m> is 0.25 (or 0.250). What is the decimal form of <m>\dfrac{1}{8}</m>?</p>
    <image source="eighth.png" width = "50%"></image></note>

